Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

This project concerns the land-surface temperature of Los Angeles, California (Jan 1849 - December 2020). The raw data was graciously provided by Berkeley Earth. The original data was recorded as the anomaly from monthly average data of each month, in Celsius degrees, but in this work, all temperature data will be converted into absolute data. The data was downloaded with the following command line command and then converted into a pandas dataframe.

In [2]:
%%bash
curl -o los_angeles.txt https://berkeley-earth-temperature.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/Local/TAVG/Text/34.56N-118.70W-TAVG-Trend.txt

In [5]:
def absolute_temperatures(df, monthly_averages):
    monthly_averages = pd.Series(monthly_averages, index=range(1, 13))
    
    df['Monthly_Average'] = df['Month'].map(monthly_averages)

    df['Monthly_Absolute'] = df['Monthly_Anomaly'] + df['Monthly_Average']
    
    return df

la_ref = [9.08, 10.53, 11.57, 13.66, 16.73, 20.36, 24.05, 23.93, 21.90, 17.56, 12.82, 9.59]
los_angeles = absolute_temperatures(los_angeles, la_ref)

The dataframe now contains the monthly absolute temperature in Monthly_Absolute. Now, I want to take out only this data and convert the index into a list of dates.

Spectral Analysis¶

To determine the periodic behavior of the time series, a spectral analysis technique is employed. The periodogram was illustrated to determine the seasonality $s$ to be used in the SARIMA model.

In [7]:
la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'] = la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].dropna()
print(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].isna().sum())

power_spectrum = np.abs(fft(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].to_numpy())) ** 2
frequencies = fftfreq(len(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].to_numpy()), 1)

plt.figure(figsize=(5, 3))
plt.plot(frequencies[frequencies > 0], power_spectrum[frequencies > 0])
plt.title('Periodogram')
plt.xlabel('Frequency (cycles per month)')
plt.ylabel('Spectrum')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

max_index = np.argmax(power_spectrum[frequencies > 0])
ideal_period = 1 / frequencies[frequencies > 0][max_index]
print(ideal_period)

On the periodogram, there are a couple of visible peaks, but as calculated by the code above, the most prominent peak is suggesting a 12-month (1-year) period. I will use $s=12$ later in the SARIMA $(p,d,q)\times(P,D,Q)$ model.

SARIMA Model¶

Plotting the Time Series and Unit Root Testing¶

The first step of SARIMA model fitting is to plot the original data. Inspecting the plot can produce much insight into the stationarility and seasonality of the data.

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(la_monthly.index, la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'])
plt.title('Monthly Anomaly Time Series (Los Angeles)')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Monthly Absolute Temperature')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Given the abundance of data points in this dataset, it is not a responsible idea to claim if it is stationary based on the graph. I will use the unit root testing / (augmented) Dickey-Fuller test. For efficiency, I will produce a couple of variations of the data ($\nabla x_t$, $\nabla_{12}x_t$, and $\nabla_{12} \nabla x_t$).

In [9]:
la_monthly.loc[:, 'Diff'] = la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].diff()
la_monthly.loc[:, 'Diff_s12'] = la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].diff(12)
la_monthly.loc[:, 'Diff_Diff_s12'] = la_monthly['Diff'].diff(12)
adf0, p0, user_lag0, n_obs0, critical_values0, icbest0 = adfuller(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].dropna())
adf1, p1, user_lag1, n_obs1, critical_values1, icbest1 = adfuller(la_monthly['Diff'].dropna())
adf2, p2, user_lag2, n_obs2, critical_values2, icbest2 = adfuller(la_monthly['Diff_s12'].dropna())
adf3, p3, user_lag3, n_obs3, critical_values3, icbest3 = adfuller(la_monthly['Diff_Diff_s12'].dropna())
print(p0<0.05, p1<0.05, p2<0.05, p3<0.05)

Plotting ACF and PACF¶

To our surprise, the augmented Dickey-Fuller test shows that even the original data is stationary. Then, in the next step, ACF and PACF are generated.

In [10]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(6, 5))

plot_acf(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].dropna(), ax=axs[0], lags=40)
axs[0].set_title('ACF of Monthly Temperature Value')

plot_pacf(la_monthly['Monthly_Absolute'].dropna(), ax=axs[1], lags=40)
axs[1].set_title('PACF of Monthly Temperature Value')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpreting from this ACF and PACF plots:

  • Seasonal: ACF tails off while PACF cuts off after $2s$, suggesting SAR(2).
  • Non-seasonal: ACF tails off and PACF tails off within the first $1s$. This is vague, but ARMA(2,2) can be a good starting point.

The starting point of model fitting is $\text{SARIMA}(2,0,2)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$.

Model Fitting and Diagnostics¶

In [11]:
def diagnostic_plots(fitting_results, title_suffix=''):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 8))

    # 1. Standardized Residual vs Time Plot
    axes[0, 0].plot(fitting_results.resid, linestyle='-', markersize=3)
    axes[0, 0].set_title('Standardized Residuals' + title_suffix)
    axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('Time')
    axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Standardized Residuals')
    axes[0, 0].grid(True)

    # 2. ACF of Residuals vs Lag Plot
    plot_acf(fitting_results.resid, lags=40, zero=False, ax=axes[0, 1])
    axes[0, 1].set_ylim(-0.1, 0.1)
    axes[0, 1].set_title('ACF of Residuals vs Lag' + title_suffix)
    axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Lag')
    axes[0, 1].set_ylabel('ACF')
    axes[0, 1].grid(True)

    # 3. Normal Q-Q Plot of Standardized Residuals
    qqplot(fitting_results.resid, line='s', ax=axes[1, 0])
    axes[1, 0].set_title('Normal Q−Q Plot of Standardized Residuals' + title_suffix)
    axes[1, 0].grid(True)

    # 4. p-values of Ljung-Box Statistics
    lb_test = acorr_ljungbox(fitting_results.resid, lags=40, return_df=True)
    p_values = lb_test['lb_pvalue']
    axes[1, 1].plot(p_values, marker='o', linestyle='-')
    axes[1, 1].axhline(y=0.05, color='r', linestyle='--')
    axes[1, 1].set_title('p-values for Ljung-Box Statistic vs Lag' + title_suffix)
    axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Lag')
    axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('p-value')
    axes[1, 1].grid(True)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

model1 is the $\text{SARIMA}(2,0,2)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ model discussed above.

Model Selection¶

The AIC, BIC, AICc values are presented in the table below.

Model AIC BIC AICc
$\text{ARIMA}(2,0,2)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ 7421.972 7461.310 7436.402
$\text{ARIMA}(2,0,1)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ 7429.126 7462.844 7441.495
$\text{ARIMA}(2,0,0)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ 7432.274 7460.373 7442.581
$\text{ARIMA}(1,0,1)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ 7432.183 7460.284 7442.491
$\text{ARIMA}(1,0,0)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ 7437.748 7460.229 7445.995

The general methodology of model selection is straightforward: In addition to choosing the model of the lowest AIC, BIC, and AICc,

  • Prioritize models with good diagnostic plots.
  • Among models with good diagnostics, prefer those with significant parameters.

Hence, $\text{ARIMA}(2,0,2)\times(2,0,0)_{12}$ is chosen.
